</section><div class="js-fixedHeader_start article-new"><section class="container js-socialShareAdjust"><div class="row"><div class="col-d12 col-t12"><div><span class="featured_slug"><div class="slug"><a href="/ct/search?type=keyword&query=Interview" class="js-clickTrack" data-category="Article" data-action="Breadcrumbs Section" data-label="Interview">Interview</a></div>
</span></div><div class="meta-container " itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><h2 class="title article-title" itemprop="name">
					The Moral Order of the World Points to God
					
				</h2><div class="deck spacer-top-20 spacer-bottom-15" itemprop="description">The so-called “moral argument” gives evidence of God’s existence. But it also points to his goodness and grace.</div>
<div class="article-byline "><span itemprop="author">Interview by Christopher Reese</span><span class="pipe"></span><span class="postdate" itemprop="datePublished">March 17, 2020</span></div>
<h2 class="title spacer-top-10"></h2></div>
</div>
</div>
</section><section class="article-featured-image "><div class="container"><figure class="p-relative align-center spacer-top-40"><img class="img-responsive" src="https://www-images.christianitytoday.com/images/115911.jpg?w=940" srcset="https://www-images.christianitytoday.com/images/115911.jpg?w=1880 2x" width="940" alt="The Moral Order of the World Points to God" title="The Moral Order of the World Points to God" /></figure><figcaption class="spacer-top-5 spacer-bottom-5"><div class="credit ">
									Image:
									
										Megan Vaughan
									</div>
</figcaption></div></section><section class="container"><div class="spacer-top-25 u-cf social-nav-item"><link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/system/social/styles/share.css?07082014"></link>
				<div
					class="ctSocialShare ctSocialShare_horizontal ctSocialShare_fallback"
					style="display: none; visibility: hidden; opacity: 0"
